++=== REVIEW SUMMARY APPENDIX ===
++Verdict: CHANGES_REQUIRED
++
++Findings:
++1. src/metrics/_comparator_wrap.py:40
++   The wrapper-level PASS->FAIL gate can false-fail even when ResultComparator legitimately passed, because `_extract_first_reference_scalar()` picks the first scalar-looking key from only the first `reference_values` entry using a different key set/order than `ResultComparator._compare_scalar()`. Repro:
++   - comparator PASS:
++     reference_values = [{'u': 2.0}, {'value': 1.0}]
++     actual = 1.0
++     tolerance = 0.1
++   - `ResultComparator.compare(...)` skips the first dict for scalar comparison and uses the second dict's `value=1.0`, so it returns PASS with no deviations.
++   - `evaluate_via_result_comparator(...)` instead extracts `reference_value=2.0` from the first dict, computes deviation=0.5, and overrides the PASS to FAIL at lines 112-118.
++   This is a real correctness bug in the trust-gate foundation, not just a test gap.
++
++2. src/metrics/registry.py:107
++   `per_metric_tol = tolerance_policy.get(name, tolerance_policy)` cross-pollinates a top-level tolerance override into every metric that lacks its own policy entry. That does not match the documented semantics in docs/specs/METRICS_AND_TRUST_GATES.md:33 ("Per-case override via CaseProfile.tolerance_policy[<observable_name>]"). Repro:
++   - policy = {'tolerance': 0.5, 'a': {'tolerance': 0.01}}
++   - metric `a` gets its intended named override.
++   - metric `b` receives the whole outer dict as its "per metric" policy, `_comparator_wrap` sees top-level `tolerance=0.5`, and `b` is loosened to 50% even though it has no named override.
++   This makes unrelated metrics inherit tolerance changes they were never assigned.
++
++Non-blocking conclusions from the requested probes:
++- src/metrics/spectral.py:95-103 is correct for FAIL/WARN interaction. `low_confidence` only demotes PASS->WARN; FAIL is not upgraded. Repro with low_confidence=True and 39% deviation remained FAIL.
++- src/metrics/residual.py:55-110 does prefer duck-typed `artifacts.log_path` over `raw_output_path`, and `ExecutionResult` itself has no `log_path` field (`src/models.py:90-99`). I did not find a current in-repo artifact shape that makes this a live regression, so I treated it as a priority/doc mismatch rather than a blocking bug.
++- ADR-001 plane contract is currently satisfied. `uv run lint-imports` reported 4 kept / 0 broken, and `rg -n --glob '!**/__pycache__/**' "cylinder_strouhal_fft" src/metrics` returned only string references in `base.py` and `spectral.py`, not imports.
++- ResidualMetric currently does not expose inline threshold override plumbing; I did not find spec or corpus evidence that this arc was required to support `observable_def.thresholds` yet.
++- ResidualMetric docstring says the `value` field carries the attestation verdict string, but the implementation returns `value=None` (line 176). I treated that as documentation drift for now because no failing consumer surfaced in this review.
++
++Verification runbook:
++- `uv run pytest -q tests/test_metrics/test_registry.py tests/test_metrics/test_pointwise_integrated.py tests/test_metrics/test_spectral.py tests/test_metrics/test_residual.py` -> 43 passed.
++- Plain `pytest -q ...` in the ambient shell failed collection with `ModuleNotFoundError: No module named 'yaml'`; that is an environment mismatch, not an undeclared dependency (`pyproject.toml:20-23` declares `pyyaml>=6.0` and the `uv` environment is green).
++- `uv run lint-imports` -> all 4 ADR-001 contracts kept.
++- Live repros executed under `uv run python` for:
++  - false PASS->FAIL wrapper override in `_comparator_wrap`
++  - tolerance-policy cross-pollination in `registry.evaluate_all`
++  - SpectralMetric low_confidence preserving FAIL
